5|$|Most {{palladium}} is {{used for}} catalytic converters in the automobile industry. In the run up to year 2000, the Russian supply of palladium to the global market was repeatedly delayed and disrupted because for political reasons, the export quota was not granted on time. The ensuing market panic drove the price to an all-time high of $1100 per <b>troy</b> <b>ounce</b> in January 2001. Around that time, the Ford Motor Company, fearing that automobile production would be disrupted by a palladium shortage, stockpiled the metal. When prices fell in early 2001, Ford lost nearly US$1billion.|$|E
25|$|In numismatics, {{intrinsic}} value, {{also known}} as melt value, {{is the value of}} the metal, typically a precious metal, in a coin. For example, if gold trades in commercial markets at a price of US$1200 per fine <b>troy</b> <b>ounce,</b> then a coin minted from one <b>troy</b> <b>ounce</b> of fine gold would have an intrinsic value of US$1200.|$|E
